scQTLtools:An R package for single-cell eQTL analysis.

Xiaofeng Wu

Xin Huang

Jingtong Kang

2024-06-28

scQTLtools_overview

1 Introduction

Expression quantitative trait loci (eQTL) analysis links variations in gene expression levels to genotypes. This package attempts to identify genetic variants that affect the expression of genes at a single-cell level, and can also do cis-eQTL analysis, visualize the results.

1.1 Citation

If you find this tool useful, please cite:

https://bioconductor.org/packages/3.18/scQTLtools

https://github.com/XFWu/scQTLtools

2 Installation

if (!require("BiocManager"))
  install.packages("BiocManager")
BiocManager::install("scQTLtools")

3 Overview of the package

scQTLtools functions can be categorized into mainly single-cell eQTL analysis and Visualization modules. Each of these functions and a short description is summarized as shown below.

4 Required input files

The input file requires genotype data, as well as either a gene expression matrix or a SeuratObject.

  • gene expression matrix: describes gene expressions, the row names represent gene IDs and the column names represent cell IDs.
  • SeuratObject: a Seurat object, yourseurat@assays$RNA@data is the gene expression matrix after normalizing.
  • genotype matrix: A genotype matrix where each row is one variant and each column is one sample, and the scoring method is 0/1/2/3, o represents missing values, 1 represents ref/ref, 2 represents alt/alt, and 3 represents ref/alt.

The columns of the genotype matrix should correspond to the columns of the gene expression matrix.

Example

library(scQTLtools)
# load the data
## gene expression matrix
data(testGene)
## SeuratObject
data(testSeurat)
## load the genotype data
data(testSNP)

5 Create eqtl object

The createQTLObject class is an R object designed to store data related to eQTL (expression quantitative trait loci) analysis, encompassing data lists, result data frames, and slots for biClassify, species, and group information.

Usage

createQTLObject(snpMatrix, genedata, biClassify = FALSE, species = human, group = NULL)

Arguments

snpMatrix input genotype matrix

genedata input gene expression matrix or SeuratObject

biClassify whether convert the counting method of the snpMatrix to -1/0/1. The default value is FALSE

species one of human and mouse.

group Provided by meta.data of SeuratObject, such as celltypes, cellstatus and so on.

other arguments

Example

eqtl <- createQTLObject(snpMatrix = testSNP,
                        genedata = testGene,
                        biClassify = FALSE,
                        species = 'human',
                        group = NULL)

6 Normalize gene expression matrix

Use normalizeGene to normalize the gene expression matrix.

Usage

normalizeGene(eQTLObject, method = logNormalize)

Arguments

 eQTLObject    an input "eQTLObject" object
 
 method        One of "logNormalize", "CPM", "TPM", "DESeq" or "limma".

Example

eqtl  <- normalizeGene(eQTLObject = eqtl, method = "logNormalize")

7 Identify the valid gene snp pairs

Here we use filterGeneSNP to filter snp gene pairs.

Usage

filterGeneSNP(eQTLObject, snp.number.of.cells.percent = 10, expression.min = 0, expression.number.of.cells.percent = 10)

Arguments

 eQTLObject                           an input "eQTLObject" object
 
 snp.number.of.cells.percent          threshold of minimal number of cells where mutation (or non-mutation) occurs
 
 expression.min                       expression levels of valid genes, used along with another parameter, expression.number.of.cells
 
 expression.number.of.cells.percent   threshold of minimal number of cells in which valid genes express.

Example

eqtl <- filterGeneSNP(eQTLObject = eqtl,
                      snp.number.of.cells.percent = 2,
                      expression.min = 0,
                      expression.number.of.cells.percent = 2)

8 Call single cell eQTL

Here we use callQTL to do single cell eQTL analysis.

Usage

callQTL(eQTLObject, gene_ids = NULL, downstream = NULL, upstream = NULL, p.adjust.method = bonferroni, useModel = zinb, p.adjust.Threshold = 0.05, logfc.threshold = 0.1)

Arguments

 eQTLObject           an input "eQTLObject" object
 
 gene_ids             A gene ID or a list of gene IDS.
 
 downstream           Being used to match SNPs within a base range defined by the start position of the specified gene(s) or all genes.
 
 upstream             Being used to match SNPs within a base range defined by the end position of the specified gene(s) or all genes.
 
 logfc.threshold      Represents the minimum beta threshold for fitting SNP-Gene pairs. 0.1 by dafault
 
 p.adjust.method      Methods for p-value adjusting. One of "bonferroni", "holm", "hochberg", "hommel" or "BH".
 
 useModel             Model for fitting data. One of 'zinb', 'possion' or 'linear'.
 
 p.adjust.Threshold   threshold of maximal p value. 0.05 by default.

Example

 eqtl <- callQTL(eqtl,
                 gene_ids = NULL,
                 downstream = NULL,
                 upstream = NULL,
                 p.adjust.method = "bonferroni",
                 useModel = "poisson",
                 p.adjust.Threshold = 0.05,
                 logfc.threshold = 0.1
                 )

9 Visualize the result.

Here we use visualizeQTL to visualize the result.

Usage

visualizeQTL(eQTLObject, SNPid, Geneid, groupName = NULL, plottype = boxplot, removeoutlier = TRUE)

Arguments

 eQTLObject       an input "eQTLObject" object
 
 SNPid            input SNP ID
 
 Geneid           input Gene ID
 
 groupName        input group name that the users want to view, with the default being all.
 
 plottype         one of "QTLplot", "violin", "boxplot" or "histplot". QTLplot by defalut.
 
 removeoutlier    whether remove outliers. TRUE by default.

Example

visualizeQTL(eQTLObject = eqtl,
                SNPid = "1:632647",
                Geneid = "RPS27",
                groupName = NULL,
                plottype = "QTLplot",
                removeoutlier = TRUE)
